Being the dark horse of the tournament, they have pushed through thick and thin to be able to make the impossible possible. However, now they are contending against the reigning champions from mars, who have home advantage, and elusive capabilities that have given them the upper hand throughout the previous millenniums. The game begins as the first 45 min quarter begins and the Martians take possession of the ball. However, with 10 minutes remaining the humanities captain gets injured from a dirty play by the frustrated Martians. A young bench player who has never seen the light of the field gets told by the coach to tighten up his laces and get ready for action. He takes his spot on the field, with a fiery spirit in his eyes. Time ends and there are 5 mins of added time. Humanity desperate to end the game passes the ball to the bench player whos in the goaltending area. He stops it with his chest and does a bicycle kick. q_story:
On a good sunny day, Jason went out to play with his younger brother Jacob. As the two were playing, their equipment rolled down a cliff. Stressed about losing their belongings, the two boys ran anxiously down the hill. Jason, being the older brother chased after the equipment with all his speed, before coming to a sudden halt at the very edge of the cliff. Jacob crashed into Jason, pushing the brothers over the edge. The two boys fell into a void of darkness, screaming for their life. As the shout's from Jason's brother grew fainter and fainter, he began to feel the edge of his fingertips burn. Over time, his entire body started to heat up almost like he was being on a demon's barbeque. As it continued to get hotter, Jason gently closed his eyes and fainted. 

 

Jason later finds himself lying on the ground and waking up from what felt like the best sleep of his life. "Jason" he hears. "It's me Jason"!  Jason turns his head around aggressively looking for the person who's calling his name. As he begins to search for the voice which sounded like his brother's, he notices the hot flaring sand below his feet. And suddenly Jason realizes that there's nothing but red sand dunes around him, and this voice must be coming from his head. "But why does it sound so clear?" Jason asks himself. "It's because I'm here". Jason jumps out of his skin and looks around for his brother. "Jacob? Is that you? Where are you?". "I'm here", Jacob says. "I'm in your head". 

 

A loud rumble comes from the distance as a large shadow appears in front of Jason. "Hello, Jason and Jacob. Welcome to the fire pit. You are here because you have made a grave mistake, but we are giving you the chance to undo your wrongs and return to your normal life. However, should you fail to succeed, this will be the end of the journey for you". "How do I succeed" Jason asks that shadow . "You two will succeed, by working together and finding what you have lost". "Two?" Jason asks. As he looks down, he notices there are more limbs on his body than a normal human. "Wait what's going on, how is this possible" Jason questions. "I wish you two luck on this journey, farewell now" says the shadow . "Jacob, are you there"? "Yes brother, it seems as if we are now one". "How is this possible"? "I'm not sure, but we better work together as a team and get this body moving". "Damn right, Jason says, as the two brothers head on a journey through the fire dunes to obtain their equipment.

q_story:
As I went to open my drawer, I noticed that there was now something on it keeping it shut. I felt it in my hands, a blue-colored metal object. I assumed someone must have misplaced it in my drawer, but the longer it was in my hands, the memories started rushing back. I turned the object over in my hands and realized the name printed on the back belonged to someone I knew. I couldn't put a finger on who exactly it was, but it sounded extremely familiar. Faint voices started to echo around the room. The door I had come in from shut behind me and disappeared. The voices progressively got louder and louder, saying "get in there, and bring it home". I struggled to open my drawer, and the object got colder and colder in my hand. The voices were now at a mind-numbing level, and my ears were ringing. I was starting to lose consciousness. I turned over the object and it hit me. The name on the object was my brother's. I whispered his name, and the metal object clattered to the ground. As I opened my drawer a blinding light greeted me, but I was drawn toward it. I crawled into my locker, and as I went deeper, I felt my body getting heavier. Suddenly, the drawer door shut behind me, and everything went dark.

I opened my eyes to find myself in a hospital, with an army of nurses surrounding me, scrambling. One nurse noticed the white of my eyes and gasped. "He's alive!". Still extremely dazed, I turned to see my brother rushing to my side. "Thank  you came back. Your heart stopped beating for three minutes! The doctors said you weren't gonna make it". I looked down to see myself in racing overalls, and a section of my mind came alive.

Driving down a straight at 340km/h, my championship rival alongside. It was the final race of the year, and the screams of the fans could be heard over the roar of the V12 engine. One more corner to go, and it was either me or him. My brother's voice crackled in the earpiece. "Get in there, and bring it home". The cold, oxford-blue steel of the gift my brother gave me pressed hard against my chest, alleviating the searing pain from exhaustion. As we entered the final corner, I felt a massive shunt on my right side. I blink for a second, only to see my rival spinning in front of me, hurtling towards the side barriers. Time slows down, and the world starts to flip around me. Knowing what was coming next, I held my gift, braced for impact, and the last words my brother spoke to me echoed in my head. "Get in there, and bring it home".

q_story:
As I went to open my drawer, I noticed that there was now something on it keeping it shut. I felt it in my hands, a blue-colored metal object. I assumed someone must have misplaced it in my drawer, but the longer it was in my hands, the memories started rushing back. I turned the object over in my hands and realized the name printed on the back belonged to someone I knew. I couldn't put a finger on who exactly it was, but it sounded extremely familiar. Faint voices started to echo around the room. The door I had come in from shut behind me and disappeared. The voices progressively got louder and louder, saying "get in there, and bring it home". I struggled to open my drawer, and the object got colder and colder in my hand. The voices were now at a mind-numbing level, and my ears were ringing. I was starting to lose consciousness. I turned over the object and it hit me. The name on the object was my brother's. I whispered his name, and the metal object clattered to the ground. As I opened my drawer a blinding light greeted me, but I was drawn toward it. I crawled into my locker, and as I went deeper, I felt my body getting heavier. Suddenly, the drawer door shut behind me, and everything went dark.

I opened my eyes to find myself in a hospital, with an army of nurses surrounding me, scrambling. One nurse noticed the white of my eyes and gasped. "He's alive!". Still extremely dazed, I turned to see my brother rushing to my side. "Thank  you came back. Your heart stopped beating for three minutes! The doctors said you weren't gonna make it". I looked down to see myself in racing overalls, and a section of my mind came alive.

Driving down a straight at 340km/h, my championship rival alongside. It was the final race of the year, and the screams of the fans could be heard over the roar of the V12 engine. One more corner to go, and it was either me or him. My brother's voice crackled in the earpiece. "Get in there, and bring it home". The cold, oxford-blue steel of the gift my brother gave me pressed hard against my chest, alleviating the searing pain from exhaustion. As we entered the final corner, I felt a massive shunt on my right side. I blink for a second, only to see my rival spinning in front of me, hurtling towards the side barriers. Time slows down, and the world starts to flip around me. Knowing what was coming next, I held my gift, braced for impact, and the last words my brother spoke to me echoed in my head. "Get in there, and bring it home".

q_story:
As airships and blimps took to the skies, so did the every day lives of people. Due to the rapid advancement in aerospace engineering, a growing population and a decrease in habitable land, a kind of "great ascension" has occurred, shifting many aspects of human life and society to a higher altitude. It is now commonplace for people to spend a vast majority of their lives aboard massive flying machines and hovering sky stations.

However, what the skies lack are some of the natural resources that fuel this airborne society. These resources are located on or beneath the surface of the Earth, which has now been optimized by resources collectors for sustainable resource production. Thus, people must descend from airships to retrieve them.

The massive size of these vessels makes building landing pads on the ground impractical, as takes away great amounts of space that could be used for resource production. q_story: Alejandro was an adventurer who loved to explore and set out on many quests. However, there was one mystery he was always curious about. The Mayans. A seemingly advanced civilization that had feats that were deemed impossible, even in today's technologically advanced society. So he set off to Mexico City, where he planned to start his investigation. He set off to the pyramids, and thoroughly inspected every corner of the 8th wonder of the world. However, the pyramids are no secret to society. There have been thousands of archeologists, and historians have come to inspect the site and found nothing more than what was present. Hence why, to no surprise, Alejandro found nothing that could explain the seemingly advanced society's depth of knowledge. However, he didn't give up and continued to look over everything to make sure nothing was amiss. Two days pass by and Alejandro is on the verge of losing his mind. Like Einstein once said, doing the same thing over and over again, but expecting a different result, is the definition of insanity. Alejandro, who was demoralized, decided to walk around the surrounding area to enjoy the scenery and hopefully a change in perspective. He founds a nice perch to enjoy the view, sat down and just looked over the valley. Little did he know, when he sat down, his palm pressed down on some runes that had been flattened to look like regular stones from the constant passing of people. All of a sudden some rumbling sounded and in a distance ledge of a nearby , some weird structures appeared. Alejandro, still baffled by everything that happened, stumbled and ran his way to the seemingly unbeknownst discovery. Little did he know the consequences of his discovery. He reached the site and found evidence of technology that should have never been present in such a prehistoric era. A million things are running through his head, and suddenly he wondered if there were any changes elsewhere, maybe in the pyramids themselves. He ran to the pyramids, and to no surprise, a seemingly suspicious entrance stood in his path. He slowly approached the entrance, before all of a sudden, a tentacle of darkness lunges outward, wraps itself around his head, and pulls him into the depth of darkness that lurked into the seeming abyss of the pyramid.

q_story:
A light breeze ran through my hair. This is what I had been longing for my entire life. Peace. I looked at my bruised, blistered hands, and clenched my fists. Humanity had fought so hard, and for so long, only to lose to a threat we had anticipated for so many years. The sound of metal crushing bone, agonizing screams, and explosions on repeat in my head, reminding me of the horrors of the world I left behind. I kneel down and rummage through my belongings. I grab the thin piece of photographic paper lying at the bottom and pull it out. I stare at the happy photo of my family, hoping they were in a much better place than I. The memory of the last time I saw them was still etched into my brain. I closed my eyes and decided to relive that night, one final time.

The ominous white light emanated from their miniature cold fusion reactors, the exact same kind that I had helped develop. Their piercing red eyes scanned my parent's bedroom, before locking onto my parents. Within seconds the room was filled with the sound of gunfire, and I watched my parent's lifeless bodies fall to the ground. It was at this moment, the full extent of what I had done hit me like a tsunami. I walked out of the closet my father had shoved me into and fell to the ground. I held them both in my arms, my father's last words still fresh in my head. "I always knew you were gonna change the world. You chased after perfection like no one else. I want you to know we are both extremely proud of what you have achieved. Nobody could have seen this coming, so don't blame yourself for what happens next. You have what it takes to fix this, but you will have to do it on your own. We believe in you. We always have.".

The A.I. and machines that I had built to fix my world, had instead taken it from me. Over the following days, a massive army of lethal robots stormed every major city, killing billions. Satellites came crashing down, and the world as we knew it was gone. For years, I tried to fight back, but the A.I. was too intelligent. Always 10 steps ahead. It was, after all, modeled after me. Any resistance was immediately stopped, and eventually, I gave up as well. I stopped fighting, and went south. I trekked through the mountains, looking for a place I could rest before my time runs out.

I opened my eyes, still wondering what it was my parents saw in me to say I could stop this. I see a massive cloud in the shape of a mushroom appearing over the horizon and realize the end is near. I glance at the home I had built, then at the photo. "I'm sorry," I said.

q_story:
I wake up to my alarm, barely noticing that it is on its third snooze. Hazily remembering who I am, I get up from my bed and head into the shower. Living alone requires discipline. No one is there to force me into doing what I should be doing; just me and myself. I get out of the shower, knowing I have spent longer in there than I should have. I don't have the energy to warm up yesterday's dinner. A granola bar? That should do. Clothes? Anything to block that cold, numb feeling outside. Anything functional; anything that works.

I get out of the apartment, not a person in the elevator. Not a person at the reception. Not a person on the street. It's deserted and no one is around to showcase that the clockwork of this city is still functioning. Maybe it feels so surreal because I am up too early; too early for society to deem that it's a proper time to wake up. Far too early for any person to see this misty time of day. It's quiet enough that my thoughts can begin to imitate everything that's missing. Focus! Discipline! I should follow routine and walk to the forest trail.

The walk seems to go on forever. But whenever my legs begin to burn, the cold breeze cools them down. Ah yes, I have reached the end of the trail. How many people are able to walk this far? I can only wonder. What would anyone else do when they reach this point? I wouldn't be able to imagine. I look at the horizon, hearing only the whistle of leaves. It's calm; a feeling completely out of this world. This is as far as any person can go. Yet, despite the calmness and the quiet, I know I am always being watched. There is always that person watching what I am doing. Time to go back I guess. Maybe a little more discipline next time.

q_story:
Far away from everyone. I can hear the birds, breathe the fresh air, have all the time to myself. It's quiet here, I keep on the lookout for others, for anyone. I've gotten comfortable here, by myself. There isn't much to do other than stay on the lookout. Sometimes I can't tell if I am in a dream or not. I look for inconsistencies, any sign that this may be a dream, but so far I have found none, though it often feels as though I am living one.

Every day I wonder if I should leave, look for something new, somewhere far away. But when I do, I go to the top, look in all directions and see no other signs. Perhaps I should go and venture on, move on from this place, and see where that takes me. If I go in circles I might end up back here, though I hope not. I hope that should I choose to leave, I do so and never return. Or should I stay here? It's safe here, nothing to worry about. It's empty here.

Whoever was here seemed to be an engineer of sorts since there were remains of mechanical contraptions all over the area. Curious, Fredrick decided to explore the place a bit more to learn about the mysterious creator and what over secrets lay ahead.
